s so you can't track structures all the way to their sources. In such a situation, it seems probable that you would end up with ambiguous instances like this that you would have a hard time resolving without more information/expertise. But maybe Seung or one his colleagues can come weigh in on that?<\/p>\n","answer_id":1992,"question_id":1923,"up_vote_count":7}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/1923/can-one-dendrite-pass-through-another","last_activity_date":1335468827,"creation_date":1335106472,"answer_count":1,"title":"Can one dendrite pass through another?","body":"<p>While tracing dendrites on <a href=\"http://eyewire.org/\">EyeWire<\/a> I encountered the following situation. They belong to an <a href=\"http://wiki.eyewire.org/wiki/Orientation_Selective_Ganglion_Cell\">Orientation Selective Ganglion Cell<\/a>.<\/p>\n\n<p><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/SzkFV.png\" alt=\"Dendrite hole\"><\/p>\n\n<p>It's the first dendrite I've noticed with such a clear 'hole' in it, though which another dendrite passes.<\/p>\n\n<p><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/sQZPm.png\" alt=\"Passing dendrite\"><\/p>\n\n<p>Is it possible for one dendrite to pass through another? Perhaps I shouldn't have 'connected' the top part with the bottom part?<\/p>\n","question_id":1923,"tags":["neuroscience"],"score":7,"accepted_answer_id":1992,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":104,"up_vote_count":7},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/4130798b102651c9cd6b3ea83abb08c1?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":801,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/801/yoyostein","reputation":146,"display_name":"yoyostein"},"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/9bbe3bd8b81991d8ccf5c6763edb1184?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":740,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/740/luke","reputation":4547,"display_name":"Luke","accept_rate":69},"score":3,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1335452764,"creation_date":1335452764,"body":"<p>Cytokines are essentially signalling molecules of the immune system. Broadly speaking these can be classed as pro- or anti-inflammatory. Pro-inflammatory cytokines promote inflammation, and anti-inflammatory cytokines inhibit inflammation.<\/p>\n\n<p>Inflammation (again, broadly speaking) is associated with the 'innate' immune response - this is the immediate response by neutrophils and macrophages (among others), and these cells release a variety of molecules designed to damage cells around them. This is great if those cells are bacterial, or damaged host cells that need removing, but not so great if that is 'normally' functioning tissue.<\/p>\n\n<p>Aging is associated with increased systemic inflammation - i.e. a greater proportion of pro- to anti-inflammatory cytokines. The causes of this aren't entirely certain, but it could be that the adaptive immune response (i.e. the memory T-/B- cells) is not as effective in older ages so the innate response is more important, or that it is just simply left 'unchecked'. Either way, the result this that the pro-inflammatory response can end up damaging host tissues, including the brain, without the corresponding repair instigated by anti-inflammatory cells/cytokines.<\/p>\n\n<p>Any anti-inflammatory medication (e.g. aspirin, ibuprofen, or glucocorticoids) will, in theory, reduce inflammation, but by suppressing the immune system the risk of infection naturally rises, and there may be unforeseen consequences to prolonged use (the immune system does a lot more than just fend of bacteria - e.g. it is essential for tissue maintenance and regeneration), so I am by no means suggesting the use of anti-inflammatories to protect brain function!<\/p>\n","answer_id":1986,"question_id":1980,"up_vote_count":3}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/1980/from-inflammation-to-sickness-and-depression-when-the-immune-system-subjugates","last_activity_date":1335467475,"creation_date":1335437273,"answer_count":1,"title":"From inflammation to sickness and depression: when the immune system subjugates the brain","body":"<p>Recently, some research, for example <a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2919277/\" rel=\"nofollow\">this article<\/a> has proposed that inflammation can cause innate immune cells to produce pro-inflammatory cytokines that act on the brain to cause sickness behaviour.<\/p>\n\n<p>My questions are:<\/p>\n\n<p>(1) What medication would potentially help to reduce the inflammation? I am not a biology expert so I do get a little confused reading the research articles.<\/p>\n\n<p>(2) What are cytokines in laymen's terms? Are they the same as histamines which cause allergies?<\/p>\n","question_id":1980,"tags":["immunology","pharmacology","psychology"],"score":4,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":239,"up_vote_count":4,"last_edit_date":1335467475},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/b91dbbe62bb4a2696c4a431103d4f694?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":798,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/798/ben","reputation":882,"display_name":"Ben"},"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/2550aa98332616362fa07d023da45d40?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":28,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/28/gergana-vandova","reputation":5081,"display_name":"Gergana Vandova","accept_rate":35},"score":5,"is_accepted":false,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/b91dbbe62bb4a2696c4a431103d4f694?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":798,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/798/ben","reputation":882,"display_name":"Ben"},"score":0,"post_id":1973,"edited":false,"creation_date":1335435384,"comment_id":2570,"body":"Great answers thank you guys"}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1335382047,"creation_date":1335382047,"body":"<p>I think the best way is option #2:<\/p>\n\n<p>Suppose that your gene of interest is AAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAGGGGGGGGGGGGGGGGGGGGGGGG<\/p>\n\n<p>and you want to insert EcoRI restriction site GAATCC<\/p>\n\n<p>Then your Fwd primer will be  GAATCC AAAAAAAAAAAAAAAA<\/p>\n\n<p>and your Rev primer will be GGATTC CCCCCCCCCCCCCCCC<\/p>\n\n<p>But in general, it shouldn't matter which option you choose, as long as you calculate the Tm of only the part of the primer that hybridizes to your template.<\/p>\n","answer_id":1973,"question_id":1968,"up_vote_count":5},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/3bb465ba7c2338b41ef15a2a05306a7c?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":444,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/444/gianpaolo-r","reputation":3120,"display_name":"Gianpaolo R","accept_rate":40},"score":2,"is_accepted":true,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/b91dbbe62bb4a2696c4a431103d4f694?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":798,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/798/ben","reputation":882,"display_name":"Ben"},"score":0,"post_id":1979,"edited":false,"creation_date":1335435400,"comment_id":2571,"body":"Great answers thank you guys"}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1335430539,"creation_date":1335430539,"body":"<p>The option #2 is most common. Do not forget to add 3 or more additional terminal base pairs for optimal restriction enzyme cutting (source: <a href=\"http://www.biotechniques.com/multimedia/archive/00007/98244bm15_7837a.pdf\" rel=\"nofollow\">BioTechniques 1998, 24:582-584<\/a>)<\/p>\n","answer_id":1979,"question_id":1968,"up_vote_count":2}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/1968/primer-design-for-introduction-of-restriction-sites-flanking-a-gene-of-interest","last_activity_date":1335430539,"creation_date":1335346460,"answer_count":2,"title":"Primer design for introduction of restriction sites flanking a gene of interest","body":"<p>I am wondering what the correct method for primer design to introduce restriction sites. Specifically between two methods.<\/p>\n\n<p>1) Primer first partially hybridises to the gene, has a mis-match where the restriction site and extra bases are on the primer, then has a hybridised site following the restriction site, to DNA upstream of the gene.<\/p>\n\n<p>or<\/p>\n\n<p>2) Primer first partially hybridises to the gene, then completely dangling and non-hybridising has the restriction site and extra bases.<\/p>\n","question_id":1968,"tags":["molecular-biology","cloning","restriction-enzymes"],"score":5,"accepted_answer_id":1979,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":3192,"up_vote_count":5},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/EVo7J.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":790,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/790/joy","reputation":224,"display_name":"Joy","accept_rate":100},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/4e8d0828732c8eb54a0335e7eab1ec9f?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":112,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/112/michael-kuhn","reputation":3583,"display_name":"Michael Kuhn","accept_rate":75},"score":0,"post_id":1958,"edited":false,"creation_date":1335344479,"comment_id":2547,"body":"cross post (first closed, then re-opened...) <a href=\"http://www.biostars.org/post/show/43507/charateristics-of-strand-specific-rna-seq-dataset/\" rel=\"nofollow\">biostars.org/post/show/43507/&hellip;<\/a>"}],"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/47073e025b05ee4d61d720f6424d0191?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":12,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/12/gww","reputation":1920,"display_name":"GWW"},"score":5,"is_accepted":true,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/EVo7J.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":790,"link":"http:/