hable to the naked eye. You could only tell the divisions by where the (very tiny) branches go to."}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1333158179,"creation_date":1333158179,"body":"<p>Read \"supply\" as \"carry action potentials to.\" When the action potential reaches the junction with the muscle (i.e., the neuromuscular junction), neurotransmitters are released into synapse. A similar membrane depolarization occurs on the muscle cell, ultimately leading to contraction.<\/p>\n\n<p>Nerves visible to the naked eye are actually bundles of individual axons (hundreds, thousands, or tens of thousands of axons). Nerves have the appearance of branching because the individual axons that travel to muscle fibers don't all go to one muscle. <\/p>\n\n<p>For example the oculomotor nerve branches:<\/p>\n\n<p><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/wroNv.png\" alt=\"Oculomotor nerve\"><\/p>\n\n<p>So what you see as the oculomotor nerve is really a collection of neurons. Some of these carry action potentials to the ciliary muscle and some to the sphincter pupillae. These are the parasympathetic components. There is a completely separate set of neurons (but still contained in the same nerve) that carry signals to the <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Extraocular_muscles\">extraocular muscles<\/a>.<\/p>\n\n<p>This is really basic material that your professor should have explained to you.<\/p>\n","answer_id":1616,"question_id":1610,"up_vote_count":5}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/1610/how-do-fibers-control-muscles","last_activity_date":1333158179,"creation_date":1333125893,"answer_count":1,"title":"How do fibers control muscles?","body":"<p>My professor says<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>Nervus troclearis IV somatomotor fibers supply musculus obliquus superior.<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>and similarly for nervus oculomotorius III<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>Nervus oculomotorius postganglionic fibers supply musculus ciliaris, m. sphincter pupillae.<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>I understand the verb \"supply\" as \"stimulate\" or \"allow signal pass from the tract to the muscle that contracts or flexes\". However, fibers must have some other functions too. So the verb <em>supply<\/em> seems to be a general term for these functions.<\/p>\n\n<p><strong>How do fibers control the muscle?<\/strong><\/p>\n","question_id":1610,"tags":["homework","cranial-nerves"],"score":4,"accepted_answer_id":1616,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":47,"up_vote_count":4,"last_edit_date":1333130328},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/b9b0e36aef37924353f7b7b0dcabbc24?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":553,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/553/etienne-low-d%c3%a9carie","reputation":174,"display_name":"Etienne Low-Décarie"},"closed_date":1357159947,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/47073e025b05ee4d61d720f6424d0191?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":12,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/12/gww","reputation":1920,"display_name":"GWW"},"score":2,"post_id":1208,"edited":false,"creation_date":1330318230,"comment_id":1443,"body":"I think you need to elaborate more on what you are trying to accomplish.  Furthermore, you may get more help on <a href=\"http://biostar.stackexchange.com\" rel=\"nofollow\">biostar<\/a>"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/2b37134235e21817f74cd8c47eb0538d?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":284,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/284/faheem-mitha","reputation":393,"display_name":"Faheem Mitha","accept_rate":0},"score":0,"post_id":1208,"edited":false,"creation_date":1334783306,"comment_id":2415,"body":"This question I asked in biostar seems related - <a href=\"http://www.biostars.org/post/show/13560/examples-of-dna-sequence-motif-sets-for-testing-search-algorithm/\" rel=\"nofollow\">Examples of DNA sequence motif sets for test