500 mL of your bacteria, but it would be rather wasteful if you aren&#39;t certain it is useful."}],"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/35114dfb827dc71cb3a8ff281617c5b8?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":535,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/535/larry-parnell","reputation":3430,"display_name":"Larry_Parnell"},"score":14,"is_accepted":true,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/1a71658d81f8a82a8122050f21bb86d3?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":25,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/25/nick-t","reputation":1720,"display_name":"Nick T","accept_rate":75},"score":0,"post_id":1590,"edited":false,"creation_date":1333030009,"comment_id":1993,"body":"I&#39;m not sure if I&#39;m reading into this incorrectly, but does <i>E. coli<\/i> (or monocultures in general) function commensally?  e.g., if I inoculate 5 mL or 1 L with the same number of cells, will the 5 mL produce more cells (not density) faster?"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/35114dfb827dc71cb3a8ff281617c5b8?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":535,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/535/larry-parnell","reputation":3430,"display_name":"Larry_Parnell"},"score":0,"post_id":1590,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/1a71658d81f8a82a8122050f21bb86d3?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":25,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/25/nick-t","reputation":1720,"display_name":"Nick T","accept_rate":75},"edited":false,"creation_date":1333457374,"comment_id":2083,"body":"If a culture is too dilute, it can have a reduced doubling time."}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1332939742,"creation_date":1332939742,"body":"<p>Growth can be quite slow for some species under certain conditions when the concentration of cells is too low. Log-phase growth is powerful, and so one would like to keep cells in this state for the experiment at hand. Different genes are expressed then compared to a stationary phase.<\/p>\n\n<p>In addition, you'd like your culture to out-compete a contaminant if there is one. That is more easily accomplished with a starter culture, which is then used to inoculate a larger culture for scale-up. Inoculating directing into the large-sized flask may allow your bacteria to enter a stationary phase, thus giving an opportunity for other species to out-compete your bacteria.<\/p>\n","answer_id":1590,"question_id":1589,"up_vote_count":14},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/2550aa98332616362fa07d023da45d40?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":28,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/28/gergana-vandova","reputation":5081,"display_name":"Gergana Vandova","accept_rate":35},"score":7,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1332992634,"creation_date":1332992634,"body":"<p>I agree that a starter culture would out-comete a contaminant (especially if there is no antibiotic in the media).<\/p>\n\n<p>Another advantage of inoculating with starter culture is that your results concerning plasmid preps or preparing competent cells will be easily reproducible. By inoculating with a colony, the starter number of cells is different each time you do that, so you might not know how long your cells have to grow to reach a certain OD (e.g. for preparing competent cells) or you have to measure the OD before you isolate DNA to be sure that your yields are comparable with your previous ones.<\/p>\n","answer_id":1599,"question_id":1589,"up_vote_count":7}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/1589/what-is-the-advantage-of-using-starter-cultures-for-growing-bacteria","last_activity_date":1332992634,"creation_date":1332931503,"answer_count":2,"title":"What is the advantage of using starter cultures for growing bacteria?","body":"<p>Many DNA isolation and protein e