d DNA-bending propensity but\n  differentially with CpG density. As the gene grows longer, the\n  epigenetic codes seem to be shifted from variable inner sequences\n  toward boundary regions, rendering the peaks more prominent in higher\n  organisms.<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>Their data (figures 1 and S2), however, do not support a generalized increase in the 3' UTR regions in either human T cells, mouse liver, yeast or flies. <\/p>\n","answer_id":1582,"question_id":1541,"up_vote_count":7}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/1541/why-is-the-3utr-region-highly-methylated-in-most-of-the-human-genes","last_activity_date":1332864613,"creation_date":1332527681,"answer_count":1,"title":"Why is the 3'UTR region highly methylated in most of the human genes?","body":"<p>Most of the human genes are found to be highly methylated in their 3'UTR region (0.8-0.9%). I was wondering if there is any specific reason for this?<\/p>\n","question_id":1541,"tags":["dna","epigenetics"],"score":11,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":882,"up_vote_count":11,"last_edit_date":1332646559},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/3f7407d4cdbd3a90d0a9ee44498c23ad?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":238,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/238/gabriel-fair","reputation":1818,"display_name":"Gabriel Fair","accept_rate":81},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/ef067cf09ffd3cc8f069bacec73c8202?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":222,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/222/david-lebauer","reputation":780,"display_name":"David LeBauer","accept_rate":80},"score":0,"post_id":1574,"edited":false,"creation_date":1332814656,"comment_id":1951,"body":"This question would be better with more context. Trichome is a generic term for diverse, often microscopic, structures with a wide variety of functions. The question &quot;but how does that work&quot; should be a