"},"score":0,"post_id":822,"edited":false,"creation_date":1332544176,"comment_id":1920,"body":"Is there a drug treatment for this protist?"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/3f7407d4cdbd3a90d0a9ee44498c23ad?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":238,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/238/gabriel-fair","reputation":1818,"display_name":"Gabriel Fair","accept_rate":81},"score":0,"post_id":822,"edited":false,"creation_date":1345650522,"comment_id":4914,"body":"I know antibiotics would not help. But that is never a concern since it is rarely (if not ever) identified in time to save a life."}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1332535839,"creation_date":1327576603,"body":"<p>No, <em>Naegleria fowleri<\/em> is a free-living excavate form of protist that lives in warm fresh water. <em>Fowleri<\/em> finds its way into the brain by eating through the olfactory neurons in the nose where it multiplies itself greatly by feeding on nerve tissue. <\/p>\n\n<p>Once it penetrates the nervous tissue, <em>fowleri<\/em>'s feeding  results in significant necrosis of and hemorrhaging in the olfactory bulbs. The protist then climbs along nerve fibers through the floor of the cranium via the cribriform plate and into the brain.<\/p>\n\n<p>Since the protist travels by feeding on nervous tissue, <em>fowleri<\/em> could not enter the brain via bloodstream.<\/p>\n\n<p>Just some more facts about <em>Naegleria<\/em>:<\/p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Death usually occurs within 14 days of exposure due to destruction the autonomic nerve cells of the medulla oblongata.<\/li>\n<li>Luckily for everyone this disease is rare. <a href=\"http://td.rsmjournals.com/cgi/pmidlookup?view=long&amp;pmid=18820207\" rel=\"nofollow\">There were only 300 cases as of 2008<\/a><\/li>\n<\/ul>\n","answer_id":822,"question_id":820,"up_vote_count":9,"last_edit_date":1332535839}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/820/can-naegleria-fowleri-enter-through-wounds-into-the-bloodstream","last_activity_date":1332535839,"creation_date":1327546817,"answer_count":1,"title":"Can Naegleria fowleri enter through wounds into the bloodstream?","body":"<p>All the sources I've read said that <em>Naegleria fowleri<\/em> enters the brain through the nose. But lets say that someone had cuts on their arm or leg and they are swimming in water that is conducive to <em>Naegleria fowleri<\/em> growth. Could it enter the cut into the bloodstream and then into the brain or cause some other type of damage if it enters the bloodstream? <\/p>\n","question_id":820,"tags":["human-biology","microbiology","parasitism"],"score":10,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":426,"up_vote_count":10,"last_edit_date":1327593830},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/6ec38796d74b8247ad51465641599a0c?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":397,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/397/stoicfury","reputation":534,"display_name":"stoicfury"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/56a2d7c7d842d027077ef599e14dd272?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":456,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/456/amanda","reputation":101,"display_name":"Amanda"},"score":1,"post_id":835,"edited":false,"creation_date":1328452477,"comment_id":1071,"body":"Don&#39;t know about fibre numbers, but there is a correlation between fibre types and athletic ability, in that the ratio of type I to II (slow-twitch vs fast-twitch) determines whether a person would be naturally good at sprinting vs endurance activities. If you google for something like &quot;striated muscle fibre twitch endurance&quot; you should find quite a bit on that. I would imagine that your somatotypes would be quite influenced by fibre type ratio..."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/1059206e9cdfa0201e2f13d43181c730?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":66