be present in the surrounding soil/growth medium for respiration.  Therefore if there is no oxygen in the roots then the root cells will be unable to produce ATP from respiration and consequently die.  This will eventually lead to the death of the entire plant as it is unable to take up nutrients due to the lack of a functioning root network.  <\/p>\n\n<p>This is the cause of plant death when soil is waterlogged - the water fills spaces in the soil that would otherwise contain air (i.e. oxygen).<\/p>\n\n<p>Certain plants (often crop plants), rice being given as an example in the comments below, are able to survive being waterlogged and the resulting low oxygen supply. However they can only do so in the short term.  Rice plants in particular have adaptations that allow the transport of oxygen from the aerial parts of the plant down to the roots.  This does of course mean that the rice can not survive being totally submerged for an extended period of time.  Plants such as rice may have better adapted anaerobic fermentation pathways that become the main producer of ATP when aerobic respiration has arrested thus allowing them to better cope when transiently submerged than other plants.  <\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://jxb.oxfordjournals.org/content/51/342/89\" rel=\"nofollow\">Molecular strategies for improving waterlogging tolerance in plants<\/a><\/p>\n","answer_id":1467,"question_id":1466,"up_vote_count":7,"last_edit_date":1332256807}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/1466/whats-the-effect-of-oxygen-deficit-on-plants","last_activity_date":1332256807,"creation_date":1332008727,"answer_count":1,"title":"What's the effect of oxygen deficit on plants?","body":"<p>As I know all cells require oxygen. So my question is how efficiently can plants operate in no-oxygen atmosphere? Do all plants produce enough oxygen for themselves? Can they consume their own oxygen or the oxygen will be quickly lost to the air? Is there a plant that consumes more oxygen than they produce?<\/p>\n","question_id":1466,"tags":["botany","plant-physiology","photosynthesis"],"score":10,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":3360,"up_vote_count":10},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/66c66c4d97a7bc3859a85253f003e1fb?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"moderator","user_id":6,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6/mad-scientist","reputation":6781,"display_name":"Mad Scientist","accept_rate":55},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/1a71658d81f8a82a8122050f21bb86d3?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":25,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/25/nick-t","reputation":1720,"display_name":"Nick T","accept_rate":75},"score":0,"post_id":73,"edited":false,"creation_date":1323955780,"comment_id":66,"body":"Would be nice to know why some of my T7-promoter plasmids produce ~100 mg protein/L of culture and others maybe 2-3."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/2550aa98332616362fa07d023da45d40?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":28,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/28/gergana-vandova","reputation":5081,"display_name":"Gergana Vandova","accept_rate":35},"score":1,"post_id":73,"edited":false,"creation_date":1324062054,"comment_id":171,"body":"Well, the protein expression also depends on the strength of the ribosome binding site."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/66c66c4d97a7bc3859a85253f003e1fb?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"moderator","user_id":6,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6/mad-scientist","reputation":6781,"display_name":"Mad Scientist","accept_rate":55},"score":0,"post_id":73,"edited":false,"creation_date":1324062971,"comment_id":172,"body":"I&#39;m doing <i>in vitro<\/i> transcriptions and I&#39;m not translating the RNA anyway, so for me that part doesn&#39;t matter"}],"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/a147104946cdc344d420760180bb3c89?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":219,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/219/kam","reputation":2104,"display_name":"KAM"},"score":2,"is_accepted":false,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/3f7407d4cdbd3a90d0a9ee44498c23ad?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":238,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/238/gabriel-fair","reputation":1818,"display_name":"Gabriel Fair","accept_rate":81},"score":1,"post_id":336,"edited":false,"creation_date":1325473943,"comment_id":435,"body":"This would have been better as a comment. Nice find though!"}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1324904089,"creation_date":1324904089,"body":"<p>This is not an answer, but a starting point.  I found this article<\/p>\n\n<p>Bai L, Santangelo TJ, Wang MD.  Single-molecule analysis of RNA polymerase transcription.  Annu Rev Biophys Biomol Struct. 2006;35:343-60.<\/p>\n\n<p>(http://preview.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/16689640)<\/p>\n\n<p>that may contain the answer to your question.  Lacking that, you may find good starting points in the references section.<\/p>\n","answer_id":336,"question_id":73,"up_vote_count":2},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/66c66c4d97a7bc3859a85253f003e1fb?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"moderator","user_id":6,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6/mad-scientist","reputation":6781,"display_name":"Mad Scientist","accept_rate":55},"score":1,"is_accepted":true,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1332250087,"creation_date":1332250087,"body":"<p>By far the most important part is the very beginning of the transcript, especially the positions +1 and +2. The conservered consensus sequence in class III T7 promoters is <code>GGGAGA<\/code>, any changes in the first two nucleotides severely reduce the transcription efficiency. Changes at positions +3 to +6 have much smaller effects.<\/p>\n\n<p>Additionally, changes that put many AU base pairs in that region (e.g. GGUUU) seem to affect the trancription efficiency negatively.<\/p>\n\n<p>Other sequences that are problematic anywhere, not only in the beginning are long stretches of uridines or adenines. Sequences with eight or more uridines or adenines can cause the polymerase to slip, which results in transcripts with more uridines or adenines than in the template.<\/p>\n\n<p>These characteristics are detailed in <a href=\"http://rnaworld.bio.ku.edu/reprints/main/Milligan%281989%29Meth_Enzymol_180,51.pdf\" rel=\"nofollow\">the paper from Milligan and Uhlenbeck from 1989<\/a>.<\/p>\n\n<hr>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://rnaworld.bio.ku.edu/reprints/main/Milligan%281989%29Meth_Enzymol_180,51.pdf\" rel=\"nofollow\">Milligan, J. F. &amp; Uhlenbeck, O. C. Synthesis of small RNAs using T7 RNA polymerase. Meth. Enzymol. 180, 51\u201362 (1989).<\/a><\/p>\n","answer_id":1500,"question_id":73,"up_vote_count":1}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/73/which-sequence-characteristics-influence-the-transcription-efficiency-of-t7-poly","last_activity_date":1332250087,"creation_date":1323938213,"answer_count":2,"title":"Which sequence characteristics influence the transcription efficiency of T7 polymerase?","body":"<p>The T7 polymerase doesn't transcribe all sequences equally well, the transciption efficiency can vary widely for different sequences. One well known requirement of the T7 polymerase is that the sequence should begin with 2-3 guanines for efficient transcription.<\/p>\n\n<p>Is there any literature that quantified the effects of the sequence on the transcription efficiency? I'm mostly interested in the effect of the first few nucleotides, as changing other parts of the sequence is usually not possible.<\/p>\n","question_id":73,"tags":["biochemistry","rna"],"score":10,"accepted_answer_id":1500,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":363,"up_vote_count":10},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/