ecause the nest was somehow destroyed, or environmental conditions were unfavourable.<\/p>\n\n<p>I found a few examples pointing in this direction:<\/p>\n\n<p>The Trumpeter Swan page on the <a href=\"http://www.nps.gov/yell/naturescience/trumpeterswan.htm\">Yellowstone National Park<\/a> websites reports that:<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>Nest flooding is the primary cause of nest failure. Egg predation by coyotes, ravens, and otters does occur.<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<hr>\n\n<p>From the abstract of: <a href=\"http://www.jstor.org/discover/10.2307/1522356\">Nesting Ecology of Bewick's Swans on Vaygach Island, Russia<\/a> - Syroechkovsky et al., Waterbirds, 2002<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>Nest failure was mostly due to abandonment of nests in cold weather rather then to predation. Climatic conditions in spring are the main determinants of nesting success for swans on Vaygach Island. <\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<hr>\n\n<p>From this article:<\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://elibrary.unm.edu/sora/Auk/v116n04/p1127-p1131.pdf\">Reproductive Success of Exotic Mute Swans in Connecticut<\/a> - Conover et al., The Auk, 1999 (PDF)<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>Egg survival was defined as the proportion of eggs in successful nests that hatched (Johnson et al. 1992). Successful nests were those from which at least one egg hatched. Egg survival is referred to by some authors as hatching rate (Willey and Halla 1972). Eggs left in the nest after incubation ceased were considered abandoned.  <\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>and<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>We determined the cause of failure for 33 nests: 46% were flooded, 27% were abandoned, 15% were disturbed by humans, 6% were lost to predators, and 6% failed after a parent died.<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n","answer_id":1463,"question_id":1462,"up_vote_count":6},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/49e94b363348f897f337a5bce2beec20?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":68,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/68/marta-cz-c","reputation":1717,"display_name":"Marta Cz-C","accept_rate":50},"score":6,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1331976211,"creation_date":1331976211,"body":"<p>Actually, nesting failure means that nesting trial fail before offspring could even leave the nest. In case of precocial species (where chicks leave nest immediately after hatching, like swans) it means that eggs was destroyed or parents abandoned nest, as @nico point out. In case of altricial birds (offspring stay in nest) nesting failure may also mean that all nestlings died before leaving nest.<\/p>\n\n<p>for example among House wrens (<a href=\"http://elibrary.unm.edu/sora/Condor/files/issues/v088n04/p0483-p0486.pdf\">Belles-Isles &amp; Picman 1986<\/a>):<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>About 81%\n  of nesting failures (n = 30) were due to predation (contents disappeared before the expected fledgingdate). Females abandoned seven nests, and starvation (presumably because\n  of desertion by parents) accounted for one nesting failure.<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n","answer_id":1464,"question_id":1462,"up_vote_count":6}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/1462/what-does-nesting-failure-mean","last_activity_date":1332007744,"creation_date":1331969920,"answer_count":2,"title":"What does \"nesting failure\" mean?","body":"<p>According to <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Swan\">the Wikipedia article on swans<\/a>, swans are mostly monogamous but may sometimes separate, particularly after a \"nesting failure\". What \"nesting failure\" may mean is not entirely clear to me. Does it mean that they they have literally failed to build a physical nest? Or is it that they have failed to produce offspring? Or is it something else entirely?<\/p>\n","question_id":1462,"tags":["ethology"],"score":9,"accepted_answer_id":1463,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":711,"up_vote_count":9,"last_edit_date":1332007744},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/1379a548b0ecfcbe5fe13f3bf1984a2b?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":51,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/51/mac-cowell","reputation":692,"display_name":"Mac Cowell"},"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/222b478bab6d59dc5de514a87dba88cd?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":389,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/389/bobthejoe","reputation":4911,"display_name":"bobthejoe","accept_rate":53},"score":11,"is_accepted":true,"comments":[{"owner":{"user_type":"does_not_exist","display_name":"user560"},"score":1,"post_id":1443,"edited":false,"creation_date":1331861879,"comment_id":1788,"body":"A single vortex is essential for any &quot;wet-lab&quot; for the reason bobthejoe describes. The vortex not only provides a different profile of mixing, but has the power to mix viscous fluids that would otherwise remain virtually unmixed (glycerol stocks come to mind). Vortex shakers are contra-indicated for some lab protocols (like in miniprep kits) but can be used for most mixing needs. As an aside, vortexing of DNA is safe in my experience. Genomic DNA tends to shear if precipitated and then vortexed, but plasmid DNA and oligos are fine."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/1379a548b0ecfcbe5fe13f3bf1984a2b?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":51,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/51/mac-cowell","reputation":692,"display_name":"Mac Cowell"},"score":1,"post_id":1443,"edited":false,"creation_date":1331868344,"comment_id":1793,"body":"Vortexing is called for when one or more of the fluid samples is more viscous than water?  For instance (as you suggest), 100% glycerol is 1000x more dynamically viscous than water, hence the need for a vortexer to mix water and glycerol well (<a href=\"http://www.wolframalpha.com/input/?i=viscosity%20of%20glycerol%20%2F%20viscosity%20of%20water\" rel=\"nofollow\">wolframalpha.com/input/&hellip;<\/a>)."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/1379a548b0ecfcbe5fe13f3bf1984a2b?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":51,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/51/mac-cowell","reputation":692,"display_name":"Mac Cowell"},"score":0,"post_id":1443,"edited":false,"creation_date":1331868387,"comment_id":1794,"body":"Besides mixing fluids of different viscosities, are vortexers necessary for any other lab operations?"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/222b478bab6d59dc5de514a87dba88cd?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":389,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/389/bobthejoe","reputation":4911,"display_name":"bobthejoe","accept_rate":53},"score":0,"post_id":1443,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/1379a548b0ecfcbe5fe13f3bf1984a2b?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":51,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/51/mac-cowell","reputation":692,"display_name":"Mac Cowell"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1331873495,"comment_id":1795,"body":"@Maccowell, doesn&#39;t mixing liquids of different viscosities describe most lab operation? I would also include suspending non-soluble mixtures."}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1331856159,"creation_date":1331856159,"body":"<p>In my experience, shaking and mixing have different \"dead spaces\". Supposed you had an eppendorf tube and you stirred it around with a pipet tip for thirty minutes. You would have great convective mixing in the radial direction but virtually no mixing in the Z-direction. Supposed you had a very viscous fluid like PEG. If you set the tube on a shaker for an hour it will virtually not mix. The vortexer provides a very different profile of mixing.<\/p>\n\n<p>Instances where I wouldn't use the vortexer would be for sensitive objects like DNA and cells. <\/p>\n","answer_id":1443,"question_id":1442,"up_vote_count":11},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/ef067cf09ffd3cc8f069bacec73c8202?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":222,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/222/david-lebauer","reputation":780,"display_name":"David LeBauer","accept_rate":80},"score":9,"is_accepted":false,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/55b2cca3b7a11df3a961d57a68705503?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":43,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/43/daniel-standage","reputation":3502,"display_name":"Daniel Standage","accept_rate":76},"score":0,"post_id":1453,"edited":false,"creation_date":1332011247,"comment_id":1824,"body":"+1 for reducing technical error!"}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1331920377,"creation_date":1331920377,"body":"<blockquote>\n  <p>what specific effect the vortexing has that makes it better than manual shaking<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>In addition to @bobthejoe's answer about viscous fluids, (manual) mechanical shaking is also less consistent and more tiresome than vortexing.<\/p>\n\n<p>If the vortexer is always at the same speed and each sample is vortexed for the same amount of time, then the shaking step will be less variable among samples. For example, the vigor of mixing an aqueous soil suspension could potentially affect the amount of aggregate decomposition and release of molecules into the suspension (I don't have a reference for this, but it is good practice to treat replicates the same to minimize any non-treatment effect).<\/p>\n\n<p>Manual shaking is not only less consistent, it is also tiresome - especially with larger volumes (>=10ml) and large sample sizes.<\/p>\n","answer_id":1453,"question_id":1442,"up_vote_count":9}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/1442/what-effect-does-vortexing-have-on-a-fluid-sample-that-simple-mechanical-shaking","last_activity_date":1331920377,"creation_date":1331850737,"answer_count":2,"title":"What effect does 